==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Silt
<hw>Silt</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧lt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>silte</ets> gravel, fr. <ets>silen</ets> to drain, E.
<ets>sile</ets>; probably of Scand. origin; cf. Sw. <ets>sila</ets>,
prob. akin to AS. <ets>se⟦oacute⟧n</ets> to filter,
<ets>s⟦imac⟧gan</ets> to fall, sink, cause to sink, G. <ets>seihen</ets>
to strain, to filter, OHG. <ets>s⟦imac⟧han</ets>, Icel.
<ets>s⟦imac⟧a</ets>, Skr. <ets>sic</ets> to pour; cf. Gr.
<grk>'ikma`s</grk> moisture. Cf. <er>Sig</er>, <er>Sile</er>.]</ety>
<def>Mud or fine earth deposited from running or standing
water.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Silt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Silt
<hw>Silt</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Silted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Silting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To choke, fill, or obstruct with
silt or mud.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Silt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Silt
<hw>Silt</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To flow through crevices; to
percolate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Silty</ent>⟦br⟧
